1
00:00:00,006 --> 00:00:02,000
- [Instructor] Welcome back.

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:06,006
Today we're going to learn about closures in JavaScript.

3
00:00:06,006 --> 00:00:11,000
Closures are a powerful feature that allow an inner function

4
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:13,007
to access variables from its outer function.

5
00:00:13,007 --> 00:00:16,003
This is especially useful for managing state

6
00:00:16,003 --> 00:00:20,001
and keeping track of data over time.

7
00:00:20,001 --> 00:00:23,003
Let's learn a little bit more about closures.

8
00:00:23,003 --> 00:00:26,004
A closure is a function that remembers the variables

9
00:00:26,004 --> 00:00:28,006
from the place where it was created,

10
00:00:28,006 --> 00:00:32,000
even when the function is executed in a different context.

11
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:33,008
Think of it like a backpack.


12
00:00:33,008 --> 00:00:35,005
When the function is created,

13
00:00:35,005 --> 00:00:38,000
it packs some variables in its backpack.

14
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:39,006
No matter where the function goes,

15
00:00:39,006 --> 00:00:42,006
it carries those variables with it.

16
00:00:42,006 --> 00:00:45,000
Let's talk about why we need closures.

17
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:47,005
I mentioned before that closures allow us

18
00:00:47,005 --> 00:00:49,006
to keep track of data over time,

19
00:00:49,006 --> 00:00:53,002
and this is really key in situations where we're working

20
00:00:53,002 --> 00:00:55,008
with asynchronous operations,

21
00:00:55,008 --> 00:00:57,006
which we'll learn about a little later,

22
00:00:57,006 --> 00:01:01,002
or when dealing with event listeners.

23
00:01:01,002 --> 00:01:04,000
In our draggable terrarium, we need to keep track

24
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:05,004
of the position of the mouse

25
00:01:05,004 --> 00:01:08,001
and the element while it's being dragged.


26
00:01:08,001 --> 00:01:11,001
So what we'll need to do is keep track of some state

27
00:01:11,001 --> 00:01:15,001
between the start and end of this operation,

28
00:01:15,001 --> 00:01:20,007
and this is where our closure will be particularly useful.

29
00:01:20,007 --> 00:01:24,009
In our last lesson, we talked about event handling

30
00:01:24,009 --> 00:01:27,000
and how specific functions carry out

31
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:30,006
specific event handling tasks for us.

32
00:01:30,006 --> 00:01:34,004
As we can see in our code, quite a few of our functions here

33
00:01:34,004 --> 00:01:37,006
need to know the mouse position.

34
00:01:37,006 --> 00:01:40,001
However, dragElement is a function

35
00:01:40,001 --> 00:01:43,009
that stores our cursor position variables.


36
00:01:43,009 --> 00:01:46,001
How can we reconfigure our code

37
00:01:46,001 --> 00:01:48,007
so that all functions have access

38
00:01:48,007 --> 00:01:52,001
to these four position variables?

39
00:01:52,001 --> 00:01:54,001
This is where closures come in.

40
00:01:54,001 --> 00:01:58,004
We said that closures consist of outer and inner functions.

41
00:01:58,004 --> 00:02:00,004
So in this case, since dragElement

42
00:02:00,004 --> 00:02:02,004
is storing these four variables,

43
00:02:02,004 --> 00:02:06,009
we'll want to make dragElement the outer function.

44
00:02:06,009 --> 00:02:08,003
So let's get coding.

45
00:02:08,003 --> 00:02:11,001
First thing I'm going to do is take my cursor over here

46
00:02:11,001 --> 00:02:13,003
and confirm that the curly braces

47
00:02:13,003 --> 00:02:17,007
for my dragElement function are where I expect them to be.


48
00:02:17,007 --> 00:02:20,007
I can rely on Visual Studio Code to do this.

49
00:02:20,007 --> 00:02:23,002
And I can see here that when I put my cursor

50
00:02:23,002 --> 00:02:25,004
next to my closing curly brace,

51
00:02:25,004 --> 00:02:28,004
my opening curly brace is highlighted.

52
00:02:28,004 --> 00:02:31,006
Since I verified my closing curly brace,

53
00:02:31,006 --> 00:02:34,008
I'll go ahead and delete that curly brace.

54
00:02:34,008 --> 00:02:38,007
Then I'll scroll all the way to the bottom

55
00:02:38,007 --> 00:02:42,006
and add my closing curly brace at the bottom of my code.

56
00:02:42,006 --> 00:02:46,001
You probably notice that when I deleted that curly brace,

57
00:02:46,001 --> 00:02:48,008
I had a bunch of squiggly lines all over my code.


58
00:02:48,008 --> 00:02:51,008
That's just letting me know I'm missing a line of code.

59
00:02:51,008 --> 00:02:54,008
Visual Studio Code is really great at letting us know

60
00:02:54,008 --> 00:02:56,008
when our syntax is off.

61
00:02:56,008 --> 00:03:00,002
Okay, so I've added my curly brace,

62
00:03:00,002 --> 00:03:02,001
and now all of my inner functions

63
00:03:02,001 --> 00:03:05,007
are inside of the dragElement outer function.

64
00:03:05,007 --> 00:03:08,007
We've successfully created closure.

65
00:03:08,007 --> 00:03:11,004
Let's go back to that backpack analogy.

66
00:03:11,004 --> 00:03:14,002
You put your items, which we can consider as variables

67
00:03:14,002 --> 00:03:17,007
in your backpack, which is our closure.

68
00:03:17,007 --> 00:03:20,002
So during our trip, no matter where you are,

69
00:03:20,002 --> 00:03:22,002
you can take your items out of your backpack

70
00:03:22,002 --> 00:03:24,000
when it's needed.


71
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:27,002
And in this case, the functions inside dragElement

72
00:03:27,002 --> 00:03:29,002
carry the position variables with them

73
00:03:29,002 --> 00:03:33,006
and use them as needed during the dragging process.

74
00:03:33,006 --> 00:03:36,008
So in the case of a function like elementDrag,

75
00:03:36,008 --> 00:03:40,001
which is called repeatedly adjusting the element's position,

76
00:03:40,001 --> 00:03:43,008
it uses the same pos1, 2, 3, and 4 variables

77
00:03:43,008 --> 00:03:46,008
to calculate the new position.

78
00:03:46,008 --> 00:03:51,007
This is the case for pointerDrag as well as stopElementDrag.

79
00:03:51,007 --> 00:03:53,002
One last step I want to take here

80
00:03:53,002 --> 00:03:56,003
is move the two dragElement function calls

81
00:03:56,003 --> 00:04:01,003
on line six and seven outside of my closure.


82
00:04:01,003 --> 00:04:05,001
I hope you understand now why these two lines of code

83
00:04:05,001 --> 00:04:07,008
didn't work in our prior lesson.

84
00:04:07,008 --> 00:04:10,002
Without closures, the inner functions

85
00:04:10,002 --> 00:04:12,004
would lose track of the position variables,

86
00:04:12,004 --> 00:04:15,008
and the drag and drop functionality wouldn't work.

87
00:04:15,008 --> 00:04:18,007
Closures allow these inner functions to maintain access

88
00:04:18,007 --> 00:04:20,005
to the necessary variables,

89
00:04:20,005 --> 00:04:24,007
ensuring the elements can be correctly dragged and dropped.

90
00:04:24,007 --> 00:04:27,004
So let's go ahead and give our terrarium a spin.

91
00:04:27,004 --> 00:04:31,000
We can see in our code here that only plant1 and plant2

92
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,002
are draggable at this time.


93
00:04:33,002 --> 00:04:35,007
And don't worry, we'll fix this up soon

94
00:04:35,007 --> 00:04:40,004
so that the other plants also have the same functionality.

95
00:04:40,004 --> 00:04:43,007
For now, let's test plants one and two,

96
00:04:43,007 --> 00:04:49,004
and those plants are at the top left of our page.

97
00:04:49,004 --> 00:04:52,002
And we can see here that we were easily able

98
00:04:52,002 --> 00:04:56,007
to drag our two plants into our terrarium.

99
00:04:56,007 --> 00:04:58,004
We can also see that we can't drag

100
00:04:58,004 --> 00:05:02,007
these other plants quite yet, but we'll get there shortly.

101
00:05:02,007 --> 00:05:06,007
Congratulations, we've made our terrarium interactive,

102
00:05:06,007 --> 00:05:08,004
thanks to closures.


103
00:05:08,004 --> 00:05:10,007
In the next lesson, we'll put it all together.

104
00:05:10,007 --> 00:05:20,007
See you there.

